{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488670"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:52:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:52:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"506"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/506"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.09,0.08,0.22,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"506"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53812"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/506"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"506"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39267"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1154"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"},{"type":"tags","id":"3856"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16151"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53812"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a two-day history of increasing photophobia, pain, redness and blurring of vision in her left eye. She had a similar episode 12 months earlier, but those symptoms were mild and she did not seek medical attention. She has no significant medical history, does not take any regular medications and has not had any any recent illnesses or eye trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her visual acuity in the right eye is 6/6 and 6/18 in the left. There is miosis on the left, with a clear cornea. The right eye is normal, apart from some increased sensitivity to light - but not as sensitive as on the left.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical prednisolone and cyclopentolate","Atropine eye drops","Chloramphenicol drops","Topical prednisolone and oral diclofenac","Intravenous acetazolamide and topical timolol"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has uveitis - intraocular inflammation of the uveal tract (iris, ciliary body and choroid, with potential extension into adjacent structures). Uveitis can be classified according to the anatomical parts of the eye affected, or by the underlying cause. The causes may be classified as:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInfectious (eg HSV, TB, toxoplasmosis, HIV)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-infectious with systemic disease (eg ankylosing spondylitis, inflammatory bowel disease)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-infectious without systemic disease (eg trauma, drugs)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMasquerade (eg lymphoma)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe commonest cause of uveitis in developed countries is an autoimmune process, but in about two-thirds of cases, no cause will be found. In most of the unknown two-thirds, there is likely to an autoimmune cause, but there is usually no proof of such as diagnosis. The main aim of treatment is control and prevention of ocular inflammation and this patients requires an anti-inflammatory agent and a cycloplegic (such as\u003Cstrong\u003E topical prednisolone and cyclopentolate)\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESteroids and an anti-inflammatory \u003Cstrong\u003E(eg. topical prednisolone and oral diclofenac) \u003C/strong\u003Emight be appropriate for a diagnosis of scleritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetazolamide and timolol\u003C/strong\u003E might be an effective strategy for lowering the intra-ocular pressure in acute angle-closure glaucoma which is not present in this case.  Acute angle closure glaucoma would also present with severe eye pain and visual loss, but the pupil would be fixed and mid-dilated with a hazy cornea and likely a red and hard eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe does not require antibiotics (eg. \u003Cstrong\u003Echloramphenicol drops\u003C/strong\u003E) as there is no evidence that this is an infectious process.  Conjunctivitis or blepharitis may present with blurring of vision from the fluid and mild discomfort, but would not present with moisis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Eatropine\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to produce mydriasis and cycloplegia, and can be used in the treatment of uveitis, its main use is to produce pupillary dilatation for formal eye examination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of uveitis will not have a clearly defined cause.","Uveitis should be considered for painful acutely red eyes."],"references":["Krishna U, Ajanaku D, Denniston AK, Gkika T. Uveitis: a sight-threatening disease which can impact all systems. Postgrad Med J. 2017;93:766-73. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28942431/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39267"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"506"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39267","links"